{"id":"1709.09277","submitter":"Adrian Ezequiel Rubio Lopez","authors":"Adri\\'an E. Rubio L\\'opez, Pablo M. Poggi, Fernando C. Lombardo and\n  Vincenzo Giannini","title":"Landauer's formula breakdown for radiative heat transfer and\n  non-equilibrium Casimir forces","comments":"To appear in Physical Review A. 21 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 97, 042508 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.97.042508","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this work we analyze the incidence of the plates' thickness on the Casimir\nforce and radiative heat transfer for a configuration of parallel plates in a\nnon-equilibrium scenario, relating to Lifshitz's and Landauer's formulas. From\na first-principles canonical quantization scheme for the study of the\nmatter-field interaction, we give closed-form expressions for the\nnon-equilibrium Casimir force and the heat transfer between plates of thickness\n$d_{\\rm L},d_{\\rm R}$. We distinguish three different contributions to the\nCasimir force and to the heat transfer in the general non-equilibrium\nsituation: two associated to each of the plates, and one to the initial state\nof the field. We analyze the dependence of the Casimir force and heat transfer\nwith the plate thickness (setting $d_{\\rm L}=d_{\\rm R}\\equiv d$), showing the\nscale at which each magnitude converges to the value of infinite thickness\n($d\\rightarrow+\\infty$) and how to correctly reproduce the non-equilibrium\nLifshitz's formula. For the heat transfer, we show that Landauer's formula does\nnot apply to every case (where the three contributions are present), but it is\ncorrect for some specific situations. We also analyze the interplay of the\ndifferent contributions for realistic experimental and nanotechnological\nconditions, showing the impact of the thickness in the measurements. For small\nthickness (compared to the separation distance), the plates act to decrease the\nbackground blackbody flux, while for large thickness the heat is given by the\nbaths' contribution only. The combination of these behaviors allows for the\npossibility of having a tunable minimum in the heat transfer that is\nexperimentally attainable and observable for metals, and also of having\nvanishing heat flux in the gap when those difference are of opposite signs\n(thermal shielding). These features turns out to be relevant for\nnanotechnological applications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Sep 2017 22:34:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 8 Apr 2018 16:27:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-05-09"}
